@add canonical links to libressl.org

ok tj, bcook
@
text
@<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01 Transitional//EN">
<html>
<head>
<title>LibreSSL: Release Signing</title>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="copyright" content="This document copyright 2016 by OpenBSD.">
<link rel="canonical" href="https://www.libressl.org/signing.html">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#23238E">

<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
<link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="openbsd.css">

<h2>
<a href="index.html">
<font color="#0000ff"><i>Libre</i></font><font color="#000084">SSL</font></a>
<font color="#e00000">Release Signing</font>
</h2>
<hr>

<p>
LibreSSL portable releases are signed with a
<a href="http://man.openbsd.org/?query=signify&sektion=1">signify(1)</a>
public key:
<a href="https://github.com/libressl-portable/portable/commit/c5c2aa37be6134f6552070ab21f49d53ebfe86e6">RWQg/nutTVqCUVUw8OhyHt9n51IC8mdQRd1b93dOyVrwtIXmMI+dtGFe</a>

<p>
They are co-signed with GPG using this <a href="https://ftp.openbsd.org/pub/OpenBSD/LibreSSL/libressl.asc">public key</a>.

<p>
Release signatures can be verified using the signify program from within the OpenBSD operating system itself, using the <a href="https://github.com/aperezdc/signify">portable version of signify</a>, which is available with recent <a href="https://packages.debian.org/search?keywords=signify-openbsd">Debian</a>, <a href="http://packages.ubuntu.com/search?keywords=signify-openbsd">Ubuntu</a> and <a href="https://aur.archlinux.org/packages/signify/">Arch Linux</a></li> releases, or by using GPG.

</body>
</html>
@


